{quote}
The *supported* encoding is AL32UTF8 (the Oracle equivalent of Unicode UTF-8).
{quote}

h3. Steps to Reproduce:
# Install JIRA;
# Install Crowd;
# Configure Crowd to connect to a Delegated LDAP Directory;
# Configure JIRA to use Crowd;
# And [enable SSO in JIRA|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/CROWD/Integrating+Crowd+with+Atlassian+JIRA#IntegratingCrowdwithAtlassianJIRA-2.2ConfigureJIRAtouseCrowd%27sAuthenticatortoenableSSO(Optional)];
# Using an user that does not yet exist in JIRA or Crowd, but that exists in the LDAP Directory, try to log into JIRA.

h3. Expected Behavior:
The user would be created in Crowd and in JIRA, and would've been logged into JIRA.

h3. Actual Behavior:
The user is created in Crowd, but not in JIRA, which displays the following message:
{panel:borderStyle=solid| bgColor=#D04437| borderColor=#D04437}
!https://jira.atlassian.com/images/icons/icon-error.png!   {color:white}Sorry, your username and password are incorrect - please try again.{color}
{panel}

h5. NOTES:
This was reproduced using:
* JIRA 6.2.7;
* Crowd 2.7.2, and;
* Microsoft Active Directory.

JIRA will only allow the user to log in after the Crowd Directory synchronizes again.

h3. Expected behavior
When the webhook is setup to be triggered on *Issue Updated* event, notify on every action performed in the issue.

h3. Actual behavior
Webhook is not triggered when a comment is deleted from the issue.

h3. Steps to reproduce
# Create a webhook including the *Issue Updated* event;
# Create an issue matching the JQL filter used by the webhook (if different than the default *All Issues*);
# Add a comment to that issue;
# Delete the comment just added
# Notice that the webhook won't be triggered.
